ges china's new divorce law which was enacted in 2001 reduced divorce costs especially for women by granting the right to divorce and claim damages in the case of domestic violence and extra marital relationships and by securing women's property rights upon divorce ang sun has modeled the legal change as a decrease in women's divorce costs in a household in which all the marital surplus accrues to the husband sun shows 1 that the new divorce law predicts an increase in divorce rates after the birth of a daughter 2 that the new law results in fewer sex selective abortions for the second birth if the first birth produced a daughter and 3 that the effect of the new law on the sex ratio should have diminishing returns to divorce cost reduction for women all the predictions are supported by the empirical evidence most importantly she finds that most of the decline occurred in historically high divorce cost regions which is consistent with the predictions of the model and helps rule out concomitant changes in household income and relative returns to male and female children ang sun received her phd from brown university's department of economics sun's research interests encompass development economics labor and demographic economics and health economics she focuses on intra household allocations gender differences and household formation in particular she studies how a combination of different forces in china including traditional values rapid growth and the population structure is affecting chinese families downloads audio audio presentation and q&a streaming mp3 pdf+ presentation modified february 2012 pdf ang_sun pdf 729.4 kb location philippines conference room encina hall 616 serra st 3rd floor stanford university stanford ca 94305 directions map fsi contact lisa lee topics economics health policy china search aparc search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages events of interest sex ratio imbalance and gender studies in china marcus w feldman ppt+ recent trends in chinese birth policies and demographics thomas scharping from the specter of mao to the spirit of the law labor insurgency in china special seminar the survival of girls in china and the new care for girls program li shuzhuo support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 9741 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
